The Nigerian Railway Corporation (NRC) has said plans have been concluded to reintroduce the Diesel Multiple Unit passenger train service from Ijoko/Kajola to Iddo/Apapa following the recent arrival of two racks of Locomotive engines imported from Cumins in United States of America. The importation of the engines followed the breakdown of the two racks of engines earlier imported from China in 2013 during the administration of former President Goodluck Jonathan. Lagos District Manager of the corporation Engr Jerry Oche who made this known on Thursday in Lagos said the corporation is working with officials of Cumins, to ensure that engines and coaches are coupled, adding that the engines and coaches attached to the broken down DMU will also be overhauled. It is noteworthy that the DMU coaches were hitherto used to convey top executives to their various destinations at a flat rate of N750 each. Regarding the coaches used in operating the Lagos to Kano and Lagos Mass Transit Train (LMTT) service Oche disclosed that some of the coaches and wagons are currently being refurbished in phases. He stated further that as soon as the coaches are refurbished the Lagos to Kano passenger train service will commence operations while the Lagos mass transit train service has already commenced operations once daily from Ijoko to Iddo and back. The Lagos district manager therefore appealed to commuters to desist from climbing roof top of Lagos mass transit trains now that it has commenced operations. 